Diagnosis.— Males of
Eridantes utibilis
are characterised by a large, curved embolus (E) with a bent tip (
Fig. 25
), the shape of the embolic division (arrow,
Fig. 25
) and the finger­like palpal tibial apophysis (PTA) (
Fig. 27
). Females are recognised by the presence of a pale median triangular region (arrow) and the rounded spermathecae (S) flanked on each side (
Fig. 28
).

Distribution.— Known from Québec (present records) and Nova Scotia to Wisconsin and New York (see
Buckle et al . 2001
).
